# Operating mode (post documentation gates)

The **Gate 1** and **Gate 2** architecture document sets are **`Accepted`**.
Work now splits into **Rolling documentation** (Tier C and handbooks) and
**implementation** (runtime code, packaging, CI beyond doc enforcement).

## Defaults

- **Plan mode** for multi-file or high-risk changes: use CreatePlan / plan files
  under `/Users/griffin/.cursor/plans/` before large edits.
- **Accepted docs and ADRs are authoritative.** Do not implement behaviour that
  contradicts them without updating or superseding the relevant ADR and
  architecture text.
- **Documentation-only tasks:** prefer editing `**/*.md` and `**/*.mdc` (plus
  doc frontmatter YAML). If a task is clearly docs-only, treat that as the
  default scope.

## Implementation (in scope)

Product code, tests, packaging, and non-doc config are **in scope** when they
execute the accepted architecture — not ad-hoc experiments that bypass
governance. New subsystems or contract changes should trace to `docs/` and
`specs/` updates in the same PR series when behaviour changes.

## Exceptions

- **Human override:** If the human explicitly asks to break from plan mode or
  scope (e.g. emergency fix, spike), follow their instruction and keep commits
  reviewable.
- **CI/docs hygiene:** Small workflow or script changes that only enforce the
  existing docs/specs bar are fine when requested by name.

**`REF_ONLY/` snapshot imports:** Verbatim trees under `REF_ONLY/plugin-branch/`
and `REF_ONLY/cicd-branch/`, plus generated `REF_ONLY/inventory.txt`, are
read-only reference material (not product code). Do not edit imported files in
place; follow `REF_ONLY/PROVENANCE.md` and `.cursor/rules/reference-material.mdc`.

## Why (historical)

Early in the project, Gate 1 required Tier A + core Tier B `Accepted` before
runtime code. That gate is satisfied; the discipline remains — **trace changes to
documented decisions**.
